What are HVO and SAF?
Hydrotreated Vegetable Oil (HVO) is a renewable diesel fuel produced through hydrotreating vegetable oils, animal fats, and waste feedstocks. Its chemical composition closely resembles conventional diesel, allowing it to be used directly in existing diesel engines without modifications while significantly reducing greenhouse gas emissions.

Sustainable Aviation Fuel (SAF) is a renewable alternative to conventional jet fuel produced from sustainable feedstocks including used cooking oil, animal fats, biomass, agricultural residues, and other renewable resources. SAF can be blended with traditional aviation fuel while utilizing existing airport infrastructure and aircraft engines, enabling substantial carbon emission reductions for the aviation industry.

Modern HVO and SAF production incorporates advanced technologies including:

·         Advanced Hydroprocessing Technology for high-efficiency renewable fuel production

·         Renewable Feedstock Preprocessing for improved feedstock flexibility

·         Co-processing in Existing Refineries to reduce capital investment

·         Waste Oil & Residue Conversion Technologies for circular economy integration

·         Advanced Catalyst Systems for improved fuel yield and quality

·         Digital Process Monitoring and Optimization for enhanced production efficiency

By delivering drop-in renewable fuel solutions with significantly lower lifecycle carbon emissions, HVO and SAF enable governments, transportation operators, airlines, and industrial users to accelerate decarbonization while utilizing existing fuel infrastructure.

